{"nodes":[{"type":"PARAGRAPH","id":"mfut65003","nodes":[],"paragraphData":{}},{"type":"DIVIDER","id":"r0qwj771","nodes":[],"dividerData":{"containerData":{"textWrap":false,"height":{},"spoiler":{},"alignment":"CENTER","width":{}},"lineStyle":"SINGLE","width":"LARGE","alignment":"CENTER"}},{"type":"PARAGRAPH","id":"73nkw703","nodes":[{"type":"TEXT","id":"","nodes":[],"textData":{"text":"They say opposites attract, but when it comes to electric and magnetic fields, it’s more like two halves of an amazing whole, leaning on each other to light up our world.","decorations":[{"type":"COLOR","colorData":{"background":"transparent","foreground":"rgb(0, 0, 0)"}},{"type":"ITALIC","italicData":true}]}}],"paragraphData":{}},{"type":"PARAGRAPH","id":"c86ws362","nodes":[],"paragraphData":{"textStyle":{"textAlignment":"AUTO"}}},{"paragraphData":{"textStyle":{"textAlignment":"AUTO"}},"style":{},"id":"hek86363","nodes":[{"type":"TEXT","id":"","nodes":[],"textData":{"text":"Electricity and magnetism are  the ultimate power duo—each one impressive on its own, but truly extraordinary together. Their “relationship” forms the backbone of modern technology, sparking inventions from electric motors to smartphones. To really appreciate how electric and magnetic fields team up, let’s dive into their unique personalities and see what makes their connection so electrifying.","decorations":[{"type":"COLOR","colorData":{"background":"transparent","foreground":"rgb(0, 0, 0)"}},{"type":"ITALIC","italicData":true}]}}],"type":"PARAGRAPH"},{"type":"DIVIDER","id":"l5kk4464","nodes":[],"dividerData":{"containerData":{"textWrap":false,"height":{},"spoiler":{},"alignment":"CENTER","width":{}},"lineStyle":"SINGLE","width":"LARGE","alignment":"CENTER"}},{"type":"HEADING","id":"ldwqe820","nodes":[{"type":"TEXT","id":"","nodes":[],"textData":{"text":"Electric Fields: Origin of Power","decorations":[]}}],"headingData":{"level":4}},{"type":"PARAGRAPH","id":"kpdtl843","nodes":[],"paragraphData":{}},{"paragraphData":{"textStyle":{"textAlignment":"AUTO"}},"style":{},"id":"tfsgq824","nodes":[{"type":"TEXT","id":"","nodes":[],"textData":{"text":"Electric fields arise from charged particles like protons (positive) and electrons (negative), each generating an “invisible field” that exerts forces on other charges, either attracting or repelling them. While electric fields may seem abstract, they permeate our daily experiences— the small shock felt when touching a doorknob after walking across a carpet is the result of static electricity—an electric field that builds up due to accumulated charges on the skin. Lightning, a striking natural display, demonstrates the same principle on a massive scale, where the electric field is intense enough to discharge dramatically.","decorations":[{"type":"COLOR","colorData":{"background":"transparent","foreground":"rgb(14, 14, 14)"}}]}}],"type":"PARAGRAPH"},{"type":"PARAGRAPH","id":"e9g9u826","nodes":[],"paragraphData":{"textStyle":{"textAlignment":"AUTO"}}},{"paragraphData":{"textStyle":{"textAlignment":"AUTO"}},"style":{},"id":"o7gf9827","nodes":[{"type":"TEXT","id":"","nodes":[],"textData":{"text":"A unique aspect of electric fields is their connection to magnetism: a stationary charge produces only an electric field, but as it begins to move, a magnetic field emerges, encircling its path in loops perpendicular to the direction of motion. This phenomenon can be visualized through the “right-hand rule”—if one curls their fingers in the direction of the current, the thumb will point along the magnetic field lines. This intrinsic link between electric and magnetic forces exemplifies the underlying unity of electromagnetism, revealing how each field enhances and shapes the other.","decorations":[{"type":"COLOR","colorData":{"background":"transparent","foreground":"rgb(14, 14, 14)"}}]}}],"type":"PARAGRAPH"},{"type":"DIVIDER","id":"5rg7g880","nodes":[],"dividerData":{"containerData":{"textWrap":false,"height":{},"spoiler":{},"alignment":"CENTER","width":{}},"lineStyle":"SINGLE","width":"LARGE","alignment":"CENTER"}},{"type":"HEADING","id":"vi43w882","nodes":[{"type":"TEXT","id":"","nodes":[],"textData":{"text":"The Magnetic Field: The Dynamic Partner","decorations":[]}}],"headingData":{"level":4}},{"paragraphData":{"textStyle":{"textAlignment":"AUTO"}},"style":{},"id":"im8b5919","nodes":[],"type":"PARAGRAPH"},{"paragraphData":{"textStyle":{"textAlignment":"AUTO"}},"style":{},"id":"tfsue943","nodes":[{"type":"TEXT","id":"","nodes":[],"textData":{"text":"Magnetic fields differ fundamentally from electric fields because they do not originate from static charges but form around moving electric charges, such as electrons orbiting within atoms or currents flowing through conductors. Unlike electric charges, which can exist independently as positive or negative, magnetic poles are inseparable: they always manifest as north-south pairs. If a magnet is divided, each fragment becomes a smaller magnet with its own north and south poles, reflecting the inherent duality of magnetic fields.","decorations":[{"type":"COLOR","colorData":{"background":"transparent","foreground":"rgb(14, 14, 14)"}}]}}],"type":"PARAGRAPH"},{"type":"PARAGRAPH","id":"x0nbm921","nodes":[],"paragraphData":{"textStyle":{"textAlignment":"AUTO"}}},{"paragraphData":{"textStyle":{"textAlignment":"AUTO"}},"style":{},"id":"o103u922","nodes":[{"type":"TEXT","id":"","nodes":[],"textData":{"text":"Magnetic fields exert distinctive forces of attraction and repulsion. Anyone who has felt two magnets snap together or resist each other has encountered this invisible force directly. Crucially, a magnetic field cannot exist independently of a moving electric charge, underscoring the interdependent relationship between electricity and magnetism.","decorations":[{"type":"COLOR","colorData":{"background":"transparent","foreground":"rgb(14, 14, 14)"}}]}}],"type":"PARAGRAPH"},{"type":"PARAGRAPH","id":"rzn2d924","nodes":[],"paragraphData":{"textStyle":{"textAlignment":"AUTO"}}},{"paragraphData":{"textStyle":{"textAlignment":"AUTO"}},"style":{},"id":"gprqh925","nodes":[{"type":"TEXT","id":"","nodes":[],"textData":{"text":"The connection between electric and magnetic fields becomes particularly significant with electromagnetic induction. When a magnetic field changes—whether through motion or fluctuation—it induces an electric field around it, a process fundamental to the operation of generators. In generators, coils of wire rotate through a magnetic field, and the changing magnetic flux induces an electric current in the coils. This phenomenon reveals that changing magnetic fields can give rise to electric fields, illustrating the profound link between electricity and magnetism through the dynamics of movement.","decorations":[{"type":"COLOR","colorData":{"background":"transparent","foreground":"rgb(14, 14, 14)"}}]}}],"type":"PARAGRAPH"},{"type":"IMAGE","id":"dii1p1057","nodes":[],"imageData":{"image":{"src":{"id":"11b1c4_ab5f94cc4e4347d1baa5f5f762397164~mv2.png"},"width":300,"height":250},"disableDownload":true,"caption":"Image Credit: Published by Creazilla. Author: helder100. Source: helder100 on Pixabay. License: Public Domain (CC0). Free for editorial, educational, commercial, and personal projects. No attribution required.","disableExpand":true,"containerData":{"width":{"size":"SMALL"},"alignment":"CENTER","textWrap":true}}},{"type":"DIVIDER","id":"x5oan1248","nodes":[],"dividerData":{"containerData":{"textWrap":false,"height":{},"spoiler":{},"alignment":"CENTER","width":{}},"lineStyle":"SINGLE","width":"LARGE","alignment":"CENTER"}},{"type":"HEADING","id":"v7e6h1250","nodes":[{"type":"TEXT","id":"","nodes":[],"textData":{"text":"Maxwell: The Matchmaker of Electric and Magnetic Fields","decorations":[]}}],"headingData":{"level":4}},{"paragraphData":{"textStyle":{"textAlignment":"AUTO"}},"style":{},"id":"j9hp81308","nodes":[],"type":"PARAGRAPH"},{"paragraphData":{"textStyle":{"textAlignment":"AUTO"}},"style":{},"id":"qw0k21332","nodes":[{"type":"TEXT","id":"","nodes":[],"textData":{"text":"In the 19th century, physicist James Clerk Maxwell became the “matchmaker” when he developed an equation that showed how a changing electric field creates a magnetic field, and vice versa, and he later on even predicted that light itself is an electromagnetic wave where electric and magnetic fields oscillate in perfect harmony.","decorations":[{"type":"COLOR","colorData":{"background":"transparent","foreground":"rgb(14, 14, 14)"}}]}}],"type":"PARAGRAPH"},{"type":"PARAGRAPH","id":"0dbpw1432","nodes":[],"paragraphData":{}},{"type":"HTML","id":"iuvbt1431","nodes":[],"htmlData":{"containerData":{"textWrap":true,"height":{"custom":"550"},"spoiler":{},"alignment":"CENTER","width":{"custom":"516"}},"html":"<!DOCTYPE html>
